title: Generate Kaplan-Meier curves plot for time-to-event analysis
text: kmcurvely R package creates Kaplan-Meier curves plot clinical trial analysis reporting terms time--event analysis. interactive features, users can: Search ENDPOINT SUBGROUP interest. Selection view single/multiple ENDPOINT SUBGROUP interest.

previous_headings: Procedure to generate interactive Kaplan-Meier plot
title: Generate Kaplan-Meier curves plot for time-to-event analysis
text: example presented vignette, utilize ADAM data kmcurvely R package. factorize actual arm variable, TRT01P, enable kmcurvely R package identify arm serves reference group. Manually add new endpoints time--event analysis, .e., OS PFS:
code: library(dplyr) library(survival) library(ggplot2) library(plotly) library(metalite) library(kmcurvely)  # meta <- meta_tte_example() adsl <- kmcurvely_adsl adsl$TRT01P <- factor(   adsl$TRT01P,   levels = c("Placebo", "Xanomeline Low Dose", "Xanomeline High Dose"),   labels = c("Placebo", "Low Dose", "High Dose") )  # read adtte dataset adtte <- kmcurvely_adtte  adtte <- adtte %>% dplyr::rename(TRT01P = TRTP) adtte$TRT01P <- factor(adtte$TRT01P,   levels = c("Placebo", "Xanomeline Low Dose", "Xanomeline High Dose"),   labels = c("Placebo", "Low Dose", "High Dose") ) adtte <- adtte %>%   dplyr::union_all(adtte %>% mutate(PARAMCD = "OS")) %>%   dplyr::union_all(adtte %>% mutate(PARAMCD = "PFS", AVAL = AVAL - 3))

title: Generate Kaplan-Meier curves plot for time-to-event analysis
text: use metalite R package generate minimal metadata generation interactive Kaplan-Meier curves plot. begin, input adsl data population data adtte data observation data. Next, define analysis plan, population, observation, parameters using metalite R package functions. Without loss generality, plan generate time--event KM plot combined end point sub group : Following definition analysis plan, specify details analysis name "interactive_km_curve" providing label display. define related population "apat" observation name "apat" specifying grouping variable (group = ...), subject ID (id = ...), population flag (subset = ...) label (label = ...). users wish use different population flags, grouping variables, labels, can make changes needed. Next, specify details parameter name = "pfs; os", end point. Similarly, define gender details name = "Male; Female", sub group. Finally, build metadata running meta_build() function.
code: # define metadata meta <- meta_adam(   population = adsl,   observation = adtte ) # define analysis plan meta <- meta |>   define_plan(plan = plan(     analysis = "interactive_km_curve",     population = "apat",     observation = "efficacy_population",     parameter = "pfs;os;male;female"   )) meta <- meta |>   define_analysis(     name = "interactive_km_curve",     title = "KM curves of PFS",     label = "km curve"   ) meta <- meta |>   define_population(     name = "apat",     group = "TRT01P",     subset = quote(EFFFL == "Y"),     var = c("USUBJID", "TRT01P", "SEX")   ) |>   define_observation(     name = "efficacy_population",     group = "TRT01P",     subset = SAFFL == "Y",     var = c("USUBJID", "TRT01P", "SEX", "PARAMCD", "AVAL", "CNSR"),     label = "Efficacy population"   ) meta <- meta |>   define_parameter(     name = "pfs",     subset = PARAMCD == "PFS",     label = "PFS"   ) |>   define_parameter(     name = "os",     subset = PARAMCD == "OS",     label = "OS"   ) meta <- meta |>   define_parameter(     name = "male",     subset = SEX == "M",     label = "Male"   ) |>   define_parameter(     name = "female",     subset = SEX == "F",     label = "Female"   ) meta <- meta |> meta_build()

what: Step 3: Generate the Interactive Kaplan-Meier curves plot
title: Generate Kaplan-Meier curves plot for time-to-event analysis
text: meta built described , users can generate interactive Kaplan-Meier curves plot seamlessly simple kmcurvely() function call.
code: kmcurvely(   meta = meta,   population = "apat",   observation = "efficacy_population",   endpoint = "pfs;os",   subgroup = "male;female" )

title: Design Pattern
code: library(dplyr) library(survival) library(ggplot2) library(plotly) library(kmcurvely)  # read data data("kmcurvely_adsl") data("kmcurvely_adtte")  adsl <- kmcurvely_adsl adtte <- kmcurvely_adtte  surv_data <- adsl %>%   filter(EFFFL == "Y") %>%   select(USUBJID, TRT01P, SEX, AGEGR1) %>%   left_join(     adtte %>%       filter(PARAMCD == "OS") %>%       select(USUBJID, PARAMCD, AVAL, CNSR) %>%       union_all(         adtte %>%           mutate(             PARAMCD = "PFS",             AVAL = AVAL - 3           ) %>%           select(USUBJID, PARAMCD, AVAL, CNSR)       )   ) %>%   rename(     time = AVAL,     event = CNSR,     treatment = TRT01P   )

title: Design Pattern
code: # ----------------------------------------------- # #   calculate survival fit # ----------------------------------------------- # # for overall patients surv.fit_pfs <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "PFS"),   conf.type = "log-log" )  surv.fit_os <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "OS"),   conf.type = "log-log" ) # for subgroups of PFS surv.fit_pfs_male <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "PFS", SEX == "M"),   conf.type = "log-log" )  surv.fit_pfs_female <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "PFS", SEX == "F"),   conf.type = "log-log" )  # for subgroups of OS surv.fit_os_male <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "OS", SEX == "M"),   conf.type = "log-log" )  surv.fit_os_female <- survival::survfit(survival::Surv(time, event) ~ treatment,   data = surv_data %>% filter(PARAMCD == "OS", SEX == "F"),   conf.type = "log-log" )  # ----------------------------------------------- # #   extracts the KM estimates from survival fit # ----------------------------------------------- # db_pfs <- kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_pfs) |>   mutate(subgroup = "All") |>   union_all(     kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_pfs_male) |> mutate(subgroup = "Male")   ) |>   union_all(     kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_pfs_female) |> mutate(subgroup = "Female")   ) |>   select(time, n.risk, n.event, n.censor, surv, strata, subgroup) |>   rename(group = strata) %>%   mutate(surv = round(surv, 2), endpoint = "PFS")  db_os <- kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_os) |>   mutate(subgroup = "All") |>   union_all(     kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_os_male) |> mutate(subgroup = "Male")   ) |>   union_all(     kmcurvely:::km_extract(surv.fit_os_female) |> mutate(subgroup = "Female")   ) |>   select(time, n.risk, n.event, n.censor, surv, strata, subgroup) |>   rename(group = strata) %>%   mutate(surv = round(surv, 2), endpoint = "OS")  db <- db_pfs %>%   union_all(db_os) %>%   mutate(     group = factor(group, levels = c("Placebo", "Xanomeline Low Dose", "Xanomeline High Dose")),     subgroup = factor(subgroup, levels = c("All", "Male", "Female")),     endpoint = factor(endpoint, levels = c("PFS", "OS")),     shared_id = paste0(endpoint, "-", subgroup)   )

what: Step 3: Calculate the Number of subjects at Risk
title: Design Pattern
code: # ----------------------------------------------- # #    count the number of subjects at risk #    by endpoint and subgroup # ----------------------------------------------- # time_unit <- "weeks"  tbl_at_risk <- NULL  for (ept in c("PFS", "OS")) {   for (subgrp in c("All", "Male", "Female")) {     # filter the endpoint and subgroup     db_sub <- db %>% filter(endpoint == ept, subgroup == subgrp)      # range of the x-axis     xlimit <- switch(time_unit,       "years"  = ceiling(max(db_sub$time)),       "months" = round((max(db_sub$time) + 3), -1),       "weeks"  = round((max(db_sub$time) + 20) / 20) * 20,       "days"   = round((max(db_sub$time) + 60) / 60) * 60     )      # intervals to break the x-axis     break_x_by <- switch(time_unit,       "years"  = max(ceiling(max(db_sub$time) / 7), 1),       "months" = max(round((max(db_sub$time) / 7) / 3) * 3, 3),       "weeks"  = max(round((max(db_sub$time) / 7) / 20) * 20, 20),       "days"   = max(round((max(db_sub$time) / 7) / 60) * 60, 60)     )      # time points where number of risk is reported     break_x <- seq(0, xlimit, 1)     selected_time <- seq(0, xlimit, break_x_by)      # a table summarizing the number of patients at risk     tbl_at_risk_new <- lapply(break_x, function(tau) {       sapply(split(db_sub, db_sub$group), function(x) subset(x, time > tau)[1, "n.risk"])     })      tbl_at_risk_new <- do.call(cbind, tbl_at_risk_new)     tbl_at_risk_new[is.na(tbl_at_risk_new)] <- 0      # a wide table with n-group rows and n-time columns     tbl_at_risk_new <- as_tibble(tbl_at_risk_new) %>%       mutate(         group = row.names(tbl_at_risk_new),         endpoint = ept, subgroup = subgrp       )      # a wide table with n-group rows and n-selected time columns     tbl_at_risk_new_wide <- tbl_at_risk_new[, colnames(tbl_at_risk_new) %in% c("endpoint", "subgroup", "group", paste0("V", selected_time + 1))] %>%       select("endpoint", "subgroup", "group", everything())      colnames(tbl_at_risk_new_wide) <- c("endpoint", "subgroup", "group", selected_time)      # a long table with each row for the survival prob at 1 endpoint 1 group 1 time point     tbl_at_risk_new <- tbl_at_risk_new %>%       tidyr::pivot_longer(         cols = starts_with("V"),         names_to = "time",         values_to = "n_at_risk"       ) %>%       left_join(tibble(time = paste0("V", 1:length(break_x)), time_new = break_x)) %>%       select(-time) %>%       rename(time = time_new)      tbl_at_risk <- tbl_at_risk %>% union_all(tbl_at_risk_new)   } }  tbl_at_risk <- tbl_at_risk %>% mutate(shared_id = paste0(endpoint, "-", subgroup))  tbl_at_risk_select <- tbl_at_risk %>%   group_by(endpoint, subgroup, group) %>%   filter(row_number() %in% (selected_time + 1)) %>%   tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = time, values_from = n_at_risk) %>%   mutate(shared_id = paste0(endpoint, "-", subgroup))

title: Design Pattern
code: shareddata_id <- uuid::UUIDgenerate()  surv_shared <- crosstalk::SharedData$new(db,   group = shareddata_id,   key = ~shared_id )  cnr_shared <- crosstalk::SharedData$new(subset(db, n.censor >= 1),   group = shareddata_id,   key = ~shared_id )  risk_hover_shared <- crosstalk::SharedData$new(tbl_at_risk,   group = shareddata_id,   key = ~shared_id )  risk_table_shared <- crosstalk::SharedData$new(tbl_at_risk_select,   group = shareddata_id,   key = ~shared_id )

title: Design Pattern
code: km_plot <- ggplot() +   geom_step(     data = surv_shared,     aes(x = .data$time, y = .data$surv, group = .data$group, colour = .data$group),     direction = "hv",     size = 0.7   ) +   geom_point(     data = cnr_shared,     aes(x = .data$time, y = .data$surv, group = .data$group, colour = .data$group),     size = 1,     show.legend = FALSE   )

what: Step 6: Biuld Checkbox to filter endpoint and subgroup
title: Design Pattern
code: checkbox_endpoint <- crosstalk::filter_checkbox(   id = "group1", sharedData = surv_shared,   group = ~endpoint, label = "Endpoint" )  checkbox_subgroup <- crosstalk::filter_checkbox(   id = "group2", sharedData = surv_shared,   group = ~subgroup, label = "Subgroup" )

title: Design Pattern
code: crosstalk::bscols(   widths = c(3, 9),   # 2 sets of checkbox to select endpoint and subgroup   list(checkbox_endpoint, checkbox_subgroup),   # interactive KM curve   list(     ggplotly(km_plot, tooltip = c("text", "y"), dynamicTicks = TRUE) %>%       highlight(on = "plotly_click", off = "plotly_doubleclick") %>%       # add_trace(data = risk_hover_shared,       #           x = ~.data$time, y = ~.data$n_at_risk,       #           color = ~.data$group, group = ~.data$group,       #           type = "scatter", mode = "markers", hoverinfo = "none",       #           showlegend = FALSE,       #           hovertemplate = 'Number of subjects at risk: %{y:.0f}<extra></extra>',       #           opacity = 0) %>%       layout(         hovermode = "x unified",         legend = list(orientation = "h", y = -0.2),         title = list(text = "Kaplan–Meier curves")       ),     # at-risk table     "Number of participants at risk",     DT::datatable(risk_table_shared,       options = list(columnDefs = list(list(         visible = FALSE,         targets = c(0)       ))),       rownames = FALSE     )   ) )

code: format_hr_forestly(   outdata,   display = c("n", "event", "fig_hr"),   digits_hr = 2,   width_subgroup = 50,   width_fig = 360,   width_n = 40,   width_event = 40,   width_hr = 40,   digits_surv = 2,   footer_space = 150,   hr_range = NULL,   color = NULL,   hr_label = "Treatment <- Favor -> Placebo" )

title: Format the outdata for the HR forest plot, along with its KM plots — format_hr_forestly
text: outdata outdata object created prepare_hr_forestly(). display character vector specifying columns display forest plot. Options include "n", "event", "hr", "fig_hr". Default c("n", "event", "fig_hr"). n: Number participants comparison. event: Number events comparison. hr: Hazard ratio estimate comparison. fig_hr: Hazard ratio figure comparison. digits_hr numeric value specifying number digits display hazard ratios confidence intervals. Default 2. width_subgroup numeric value specifying width subgroup column pixels. width_fig numeric value specifying width hazard ratio figure column pixels. width_n numeric value specifying width "n" column pixels. width_event numeric value specifying width "event" column pixels. width_hr numeric value specifying width hazard ratio column pixels. digits_surv numeric value specifying number digits display survival probability KM curves. footer_space numeric value specifying space footer pixels. hr_range numeric vector lower upper limit x-axis hazard ratio figure. color character vector colors use hazard ratio figures. Defaulte value supports 4 groups. hr_label character string specifying label hazard ratio axis.
